Penetration Testing Report
Hack The Box – Starting Point: Responder

Tester: Daniel Obatuyise
Assessment Type: Internal Network Penetration Test
Target: HTB Starting Point – Responder
Date: July 2026

Executive Summary

A security assessment was conducted on the Hack The Box – Responder machine to identify vulnerabilities within a simulated Windows network. The assessment revealed that the environment was vulnerable to LLMNR/NBT-NS Poisoning, allowing NTLMv2 authentication hashes to be captured. The captured credentials were successfully cracked offline due to a weak password, demonstrating the risk of credential theft and unauthorized access.

Overall Risk Rating: High

Findings
1. LLMNR/NBT-NS Poisoning

Severity: High

Description:
The target allowed LLMNR and NBT-NS name resolution, enabling an attacker to use Responder to capture NTLMv2 authentication hashes from network traffic.

Impact:

Credential theft
Unauthorized network access
Potential lateral movement

Remediation:

Disable LLMNR and NetBIOS over TCP/IP.
Enable SMB signing.
Monitor for spoofing attacks on the network.
2. Weak Password Policy

Severity: High

Description:
The captured NTLMv2 hash was successfully cracked using a dictionary attack, indicating the use of a weak password.

Impact:

Account compromise
Increased risk of privilege escalation

Remediation:

Enforce strong password complexity requirements.
Implement Multi-Factor Authentication (MFA).
Configure account lockout policies.
Conduct regular password audits.

Tools Used

Nmap
Responder
John the Ripper
Kali Linux
Conclusion

The assessment demonstrated that insecure legacy name resolution protocols and weak passwords can lead to credential compromise in Windows environments. Disabling LLMNR/NBT-NS, enforcing strong authentication policies, and implementing modern security controls will significantly reduce the risk of similar attacks.

Disclaimer: This assessment was performed in an authorized Hack The Box training environment for educational purposes only.
